    "created_at": "2025-08-07T19:56:14Z",
    "updated_at": "2025-08-07T19:56:14Z",
    "body": "> Starship uses a library that is baked-in to interface with git, not a binary. Thus the interfaces works very differently.\n\nThen what is `git_status.use_git_executable`? Is this an interface? This sounds to me, like it's using the system's `git` binary.\n\nIf every Git module had this, part of the issue would be solved.\n\n> This proposal in particular, a shell-based solution for detection, is also likely to run into performance issues as custom modules do in some cases.\n\nActually, it can be more performant, if you allow for lazy checking. Just recently I switched to Starship for fun, but I have used my custom \"Starship\"-alternative for many years, originally written in Bash, then migrated to Nushell and it is faster than Starship, because it does lazy checking. For example, to detect a repository at it's root level, it only checks for the `.git` folder's existence. Usually, this is already enough and it's super fast. If it is not detected, then the most performant `git` command is used to detect, whether there is a Git repository at hand. I had to implement these performance improvements, due to working professionally on huge monorepos. After implementing these super fast methods, there was no issue of detecting a huge repository quickly enough.\n\nNow, that was all on Bash, later Nu level. Now, imagine, the same logic is applied to native Rust...",
